/*
================================================================================
üìò LECTURE NOTES: FUNCTIONS IN C++
(Complete Classroom Reconstruction ‚Äì English ‚Äì GitHub Ready ‚Äì Single File)

================================================================================
0Ô∏è‚É£ LECTURE INTRODUCTION (Teacher Speaking)
================================================================================

Yesterday we solved some LeetCode questions,
and today we are starting a NEW topic.

The topic name is:
üëâ FUNCTIONS IN C++

Do NOT panic.
This is a new word, not a difficult concept.

This topic is EXTREMELY IMPORTANT because:
- Recursion is based on functions
- Dynamic Programming uses functions
- Graph algorithms use functions
- Competitive programming depends on functions
- Interviews EXPECT function-based thinking

So today, we will understand:
‚úî What is a function
‚úî Why do we need it
‚úî How to write it
‚úî How to use it properly

================================================================================
1Ô∏è‚É£ PROBLEM STATEMENT (Why Do We Need Functions?)
================================================================================

Teacher says:

"Suppose I give you two numbers A and B."

Your tasks:
1Ô∏è‚É£ Check whether A is a prime number or not
2Ô∏è‚É£ If A is NOT prime ‚Üí find factorial of A
3Ô∏è‚É£ Check whether B is a prime number or not
4Ô∏è‚É£ If B is NOT prime ‚Üí find factorial of B

Now think carefully.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
‚ùå WITHOUT FUNCTIONS (Bad Approach)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

If we do NOT use functions, then:
- Write prime-checking code for A
- Write factorial code for A
- Again write prime-checking code for B
- Again write factorial code for B

Problems:
‚ùå Same logic repeated again and again
‚ùå Copy‚Äìpaste coding
‚ùå Code becomes long
‚ùå Hard to read
‚ùå Hard to debug

Teacher says:
"This is NOT professional coding."

================================================================================
2Ô∏è‚É£ REAL PROBLEM IDENTIFICATION
================================================================================

The real problem is NOT:
- Prime number
- Factorial

The real problem is:
üëâ Repeating the same code multiple times

üí° Solution:
üëâ Write the logic ONCE
üëâ Reuse it whenever needed

This idea leads to:
‚û°Ô∏è FUNCTIONS

================================================================================
3Ô∏è‚É£ WHAT IS A FUNCTION? (Conceptual Definition)
================================================================================

A FUNCTION is:
- A block of code
- Written once
- Can be used multiple times
- Takes input (optional)
- Produces output (optional)

üìå Real-life example:
- Calculator ‚Üí same add logic, different numbers
- Washing machine ‚Üí same process, different clothes

================================================================================
4Ô∏è‚É£ GENERAL STRUCTURE OF A FUNCTION
================================================================================

return_type function_name(parameters)
{
    // function body
    return value;
}

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
üîπ RETURN TYPE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Return type tells:
"What type of answer will this function give?"

Examples:
- int      ‚Üí integer value
- bool     ‚Üí true / false
- double   ‚Üí decimal value
- char     ‚Üí character
- void     ‚Üí returns nothing

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
üîπ FUNCTION NAME
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

- Any meaningful name
- Should describe the work

Example:
isPrime
factorial
sum
multiply

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
üîπ PARAMETERS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

- Inputs given to the function
- Can be zero, one, or many
- Each parameter has a data type

================================================================================
5Ô∏è‚É£ PRIME NUMBER FUNCTION (STEP-BY-STEP)
================================================================================

Definition:
A number is prime if:
- It is greater than 1
- It has exactly two divisors (1 and itself)

Return type:
üëâ bool (true or false)

*/

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

bool isPrime(int n)
{
    // Step 1: Numbers less than or equal to 1 are NOT prime
    if (n <= 1)
        return false;

    // Step 2: Check divisibility from 2 to n-1
    for (int i = 2; i < n; i++)
    {
        // If divisible by any number
        if (n % i == 0)
            return false;  // Not prime
    }

    // Step 3: No divisor found
    return true;  // Prime number
}

/*
================================================================================
6Ô∏è‚É£ FACTORIAL FUNCTION (DETAILED)
================================================================================

Factorial definition:
n! = 1 √ó 2 √ó 3 √ó ... √ó n

Return type:
üëâ int (for small values)

*/

int factorial(int n)
{
    int answer = 1;

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++)
        answer = answer * i;

    return answer;
}

/*
================================================================================
7Ô∏è‚É£ MAIN FUNCTION (USING FUNCTIONS)
================================================================================
*/

int main()
{
    int A, B;
    cin >> A >> B;

    // Check A
    if (isPrime(A))
        cout << "A is Prime\n";
    else
        cout << "Factorial of A: " << factorial(A) << endl;

    // Check B
    if (isPrime(B))
        cout << "B is Prime\n";
    else
        cout << "Factorial of B: " << factorial(B) << endl;

    return 0;
}

/*
================================================================================
8Ô∏è‚É£ FUNCTION CALL EXPLAINED
================================================================================

isPrime(A);

This is called FUNCTION CALL.

- A is the argument
- n is the parameter

Argument value is copied into parameter.

================================================================================
9Ô∏è‚É£ ARGUMENT vs PARAMETER
================================================================================

Function definition:
bool isPrime(int n)
                 ‚Üë parameter

Function call:
isPrime(7)
        ‚Üë argument

================================================================================
üîü MULTIPLE PARAMETERS FUNCTION
================================================================================
*/

int sum(int a, int b)
{
    return a + b;
}

/*
Call:
sum(3, 4) ‚Üí returns 7

================================================================================
1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ VOID FUNCTION (NO RETURN VALUE)
================================================================================
*/

void printMessage()
{
    cout << "Hello Coder Army\n";
}

/*
Call:
printMessage();

- No return
- Only performs an action

================================================================================
1Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ WHEN TO USE WHICH RETURN TYPE?
================================================================================

Use int / bool / double:
‚úî When you need the result later

Use void:
‚úî When you only want to print or perform an action

================================================================================
1Ô∏è‚É£3Ô∏è‚É£ WHY FUNCTIONS ARE IMPORTANT
================================================================================

‚úÖ Code reusability
‚úÖ Clean structure
‚úÖ Easy debugging
‚úÖ Readability
‚úÖ Industry-level coding

Without functions ‚Üí messy code  
With functions ‚Üí professional code

================================================================================
üéØ FINAL TAKEAWAY
================================================================================

‚ùå Writing same logic again and again = beginner
‚úÖ Writing reusable functions = engineer

Write once.
Use many times.
Think like a programmer.

================================================================================
END OF FILE
================================================================================
*/
